"With the prevalence and importance of IT systems in almost all fields of business activity today, it is not surprising that, on a sale of a business, the purchaser will want to ensure that the business purchased has all the IT systems necessary for the conduct of that business. At the same time, the vendor will be concerned to see that, after the sale, the IT systems that remain meet its own on-going business needs. This article examines why it is necessary, before a sale takes place, to separate out IT into that which will be sold with the business and that which will be retained by the vendor. It looks at the legal consequences for the parties if IT separation is not implemented in conjunction with new licensing arrangements (for example, liability for infringement of copyright). It also considers separation problems presented by various types of IT (for example, software, communications networks, microwave links). In deciding what approach to take to IT separation, the parties will have to consider the existing IT licensing arrangements. This article discusses some common provisions in IT licences that are relevant to IT separation, as well as the considerations that the parties should take into account if IT is bespoke or alternatively of the ‘off-the-shelf’ variety. This article also considers the relative merits of transferring (by assignment or novation), or purchasing, new IT licences. It discusses briefly the separation problems in relation to access and use to data and databases (where the vendor and the business to be sold share, or will post-separation need to share, data or databases). Finally this article outlines the separation process as a whole, and what management must do to implement IT separation."
